\name{simmapRate}
\alias{simmapRate}
\title{Stochastic Character Mapping That Accounts for Rate Variation}
\description{
Standard stochastic character mapping (e.g., \code{phytools::make.simmap})
assumes the same evolutionary rate on every branch. But if some branches
evolve faster than others — which is exactly what RateScape detects — those
standard maps can badly misplace where transitions happened.

This function generates stochastic character maps that use the branch-specific
rates estimated by \code{\link{fitRateScape}}. Branches with higher rates
are more likely to contain state transitions, while slow branches are less
likely. The result is a set of character histories that are consistent with
both the data and the estimated rate landscape.

The output is fully compatible with phytools functions like
\code{plotSimmap()} and \code{describe.simmap()}, so you can use your
existing phytools workflow.
}
\usage{
simmapRate(fit, nsim = 100, rate_summary = "sample",
           Q_scaled = TRUE, seed = NULL)
}
\arguments{
\item{fit}{A fitted model from \code{\link{fitRateScape}} (class
\code{"ratescapeFit"}).}

\item{nsim}{Number of stochastic maps to generate. More maps give a better
picture of uncertainty in the character history.
\itemize{
  \item 100 (default): Good for visualization and quick summaries.
  \item 500-1000: Better for quantitative analyses (e.g., counting
    transitions, estimating dwell times).
}
}

\item{rate_summary}{How should the posterior distribution of rates be used?
\itemize{
  \item \code{"sample"} (default, recommended): For each map, a different
    rate vector is drawn from the posterior. This fully propagates
    uncertainty in both the rates and the character history.
  \item \code{"mean"}: Uses the posterior mean rates for all maps. Faster
    but ignores rate uncertainty.
  \item \code{"map"}: Uses the maximum a posteriori (MAP) rates. Similar
    to "mean" but uses the single best point estimate.
}
}

\item{Q_scaled}{Should the Q matrix be multiplied by the branch rate scalar?
Almost always \code{TRUE} (default). Setting to \code{FALSE} ignores rate
variation (equivalent to standard stochastic mapping).}

\item{seed}{Optional integer for reproducibility.}
